              "meaning": "\"To say \"\"for X hours\"\", add \"\"kan\"\" after the counter for hours (e.g., ichiji -> ichijikan). Duration words typically do not take a particle like \"\"ni\"\" or \"\"o\"\". You can add \"\"gurai\"\" for \"\"about\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "一時間ぐらい勉強しました。<br>I studied for about one hour.<br><br>三時間テレビを見ました。<br>I watched TV for three hours."
            },
            {
              "id": "f2i9zwtdu",
              "point": "Quantity Word たくさん (Takusan)",
              "meaning": "\"Takusan means \"\"a lot\"\" or \"\"many\"\". It functions as an adverb placed before the verb, or as a noun modifier using \"\"no\"\" (takusan no hito). It works for both countable and uncountable items.\"",
              "sentences": "たくさん食べました。<br>I ate a lot.<br><br>たくさんの人がいました。<br>There were many people."
            }
          ],
          "genki1_5": [
            {
              "id": "re3361mw2",
              "point": "I-Adjectives (Present)",
              "meaning": "\"I-adjectives end in \"\"i\"\". To make them polite, add \"\"desu\"\". For negative, drop the final \"\"i\"\" and add \"\"kunai desu\"\". The exception is \"\"ii\"\" (good), which becomes \"\"yokunai desu\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "この部屋は広いです。<br>This room is spacious.<br><br>あの公園は楽しくないです。<br>That park is not fun."
            },
            {
              "id": "4i6iz0p46",
              "point": "Na-Adjectives (Present)",
              "meaning": "\"Na-adjectives behave like nouns. To make them polite, add \"\"desu\"\". For negative, add \"\"ja nai desu\"\" (or dewa arimasen). They do not end in \"\"i\"\" in their base form (mostly).\"",
              "sentences": "この町はにぎやかです。<br>This town is lively.<br><br>彼は元気じゃないです。<br>He is not energetic."
            },
            {
              "id": "uobp9mz36",
              "point": "I-Adjectives (Past)",
              "meaning": "\"To put an I-adjective into the past, drop the final \"\"i\"\" and add \"\"katta desu\"\". For past negative, drop the \"\"i\"\" from \"\"kunai\"\" and add \"\"ku nakatta desu\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "テストは難しかったです。<br>The test was difficult.<br><br>昨日は寒くなかったです。<br>It was not cold yesterday."
            },
            {
              "id": "mhwy5lq89",
              "point": "Na-Adjectives (Past)",
              "meaning": "\"Na-adjectives conjugate exactly like nouns. For past affirmative, change \"\"desu\"\" to \"\"deshita\"\". For past negative, change \"\"ja nai desu\"\" to \"\"ja nakatta desu\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "昨日は静かでした。<br>It was quiet yesterday.<br><br>あの店はにぎやかじゃなかったです。<br>That shop was not lively."
            }
          ],
          "genki1_6": [
            {
              "id": "jc3o9s8um",
              "point": "Te-form (Conjugation)",
              "meaning": "\"The \"\"te-form\"\" is a fundamental verb conjugation used to connect actions, make requests, and form continuous tenses. The conjugation rules depend entirely on the final sound of the verb's dictionary form. It functions similarly to \"\"and\"\" when linking verbs.\"",
              "sentences": "窓を開けて。<br>Open the window.<br><br>手紙を書いています。<br>I am writing a letter."
            },
            {
              "id": "o2gra9kfd",
              "point": "~te kudasai (Request)",
              "meaning": "\"To make a polite request, attach \"\"kudasai\"\" to the te-form of the verb. This translates to \"\"Please do...\"\". It is polite but direct, so it is often used for instructions or asking favors.\"",
              "sentences": "ちょっと待ってください。<br>Please wait a moment.<br><br>この辞書を見てください。<br>Please look at this dictionary."
            },
            {
              "id": "m7rqsoxe4",
              "point": "~te mo ii desu ka (Permission)",
              "meaning": "\"To ask for permission, use the structure \"\"Te-form + mo ii desu ka\"\". It literally asks \"\"Is it good even if I do...?\"\" or \"\"May I...?\"\". To grant permission, you say \"\"~te mo ii desu\"\" (You may...).\"",
              "sentences": "写真を撮ってもいいですか。<br>May I take a picture?<br><br>ここに座ってもいいですか。<br>May I sit here?"
            },
            {
              "id": "dc4nwermj",
              "point": "~te wa ikemasen (Prohibition)",
              "meaning": "\"To express a strong prohibition (\"\"You must not...\"\"), use \"\"Te-form + wa ikemasen\"\". This is a strong rule-based statement, often used by authority figures or for laws.\"",
              "sentences": "ここではしゃべってはいけません。<br>You must not talk here.<br><br>テストの時、カンニングしてはいけません。<br>You must not cheat during the test."
            },
            {
              "id": "uk1vsqmte",
              "point": "Describing Two Actions (Sequence)",
              "meaning": "\"To connect two or more actions in a sequence, put the non-final verbs into the te-form. Only the final verb in the sentence takes the tense and politeness markers (masu/mashita). It translates to \"\"I did A, and then I did B.\"\"\"",
              "sentences": "図書館に行って、勉強します。<br>I go to the library and study.<br><br>シャワーを浴びて、寝ました。<br>I took a shower and went to sleep."
            },
            {
              "id": "8dkmd4c8k",
              "point": "~kara (Reason)",
              "meaning": "\"The particle \"\"kara\"\" means \"\"because\"\". It follows the reason clause. The structure is [Reason] kara, [Result]. This is the reverse of English syntax where \"\"because\"\" starts the clause. It can be used with both polite and short forms.\"",
              "sentences": "忙しいですから、パーティーに行きません。<br>Because I am busy, I won't go to the party.<br><br>雨が降っているから、出かけません。<br>Because it is raining, I won't go out."
            },
            {
              "id": "canozkdgb",
              "point": "~mashou ka (Offering Assistance)",
              "meaning": "\"The phrase \"\"~mashou ka\"\" has two meanings depending on context: \"\"Shall we...?\"\" (Invitation) or \"\"Shall I...?\"\" (Offer of help). When offering help, it implies \"\"Shall I do this for you?\"\"\"",
              "sentences": "荷物を持ちましょうか。<br>Shall I carry your luggage?<br><br>手伝いましょうか。<br>Shall I help?"
            }
          ],
          "genki1_7": [
            {
              "id": "q9p7ivf0e",
              "point": "~te iru (Continuous Action)",
              "meaning": "\"When attached to action verbs, \"\"~te iru\"\" expresses an action currently in progress (\"\"-ing\"\"). It describes what someone is doing right now.\"",
              "sentences": "宿題をしています。<br>I am doing homework.<br><br>テレビを見ています。<br>I am watching TV."
            },
            {
              "id": "c8d6fwpdl",
              "point": "~te iru (Resultant State)",
              "meaning": "\"For verbs that describe an instant change of state (like marrying, dying, knowing, living), \"\"~te iru\"\" does not mean \"\"is doing right now\"\". It means the action happened in the past, and the state continues into the present.\"",
              "sentences": "東京に住んでいます。<br>I live in Tokyo (started living -> still live).<br><br>彼は結婚しています。<br>He is married (got married -> is married)."
            },
            {
              "id": "6yo16iq3y",
              "point": "Describing People (Body Parts)",
              "meaning": "\"To describe a person's physical attributes, use the pattern: [Person] wa [Body Part] ga [Adjective] desu. The body part is the subject of the adjective, marked by \"\"ga\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "アンディーさんは頭が大きいです。<br>Andy has a big head (Andy: head is big).<br><br>目が小さいです。<br>(I have) small eyes."
            },
            {
              "id": "qbob7rzj6",
              "point": "Te-form for Adjectives/Nouns",
              "meaning": "\"Just like verbs, adjectives and nouns can be joined using the te-form. For I-adjectives, drop \"\"i\"\" and add \"\"kute\"\". For Na-adjectives and Nouns, add \"\"de\"\". This links descriptions as \"\"and\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "安くて、おいしいです。<br>It is cheap and delicious.<br><br>日本人で、２２歳です。<br>I am Japanese and 22 years old."
            },
            {
              "id": "cfiai00x6",
              "point": "Verb Stem + ni iku (Purpose)",
              "meaning": "\"To express going somewhere TO do something, use the Verb Stem + ni + Motion Verb (iku/kuru/kaeru). The particle \"\"ni\"\" marks the purpose of the movement.\"",
              "sentences": "デパートにかばんを買いに行きます。<br>I am going to the department store to buy a bag.<br><br>ビールを買いに行く。<br>I am going to buy beer."
            }
          ],
          "genki1_9": [
            {
              "id": "nm8922xbf",
              "point": "Short Form Past (Affirmative)",
              "meaning": "\"The informal past tense for verbs is the \"\"Ta-form\"\". It is formed exactly like the Te-form, but you replace \"\"te\"\" with \"\"ta\"\" (and \"\"de\"\" with \"\"da\"\"). For I-adjectives, drop \"\"i\"\" and add \"\"katta\"\". For Na-adjectives and Nouns, add \"\"datta\"\". This form is used in casual conversation and strictly required for relative clauses.\"",
              "sentences": "昨日ラーメンを食べた。<br>I ate ramen yesterday.<br><br>そのパーティーは楽しかった。<br>That party was fun."
            },
            {
              "id": "bxdm61wv4",
              "point": "Short Form Past (Negative)",
              "meaning": "\"To express the negative past informally (\"\"didn't do\"\"), use the \"\"Nakatta\"\" form. For verbs, replace the \"\"nai\"\" ending with \"\"nakatta\"\". For adjectives and nouns, replace \"\"i\"\" or \"\"ja nai\"\" with \"\"ku nakatta\"\" or \"\"ja nakatta\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "昨日テレビを見なかった。<br>I didn't watch TV yesterday.<br><br>その映画は面白くなかった。<br>That movie wasn't interesting."
            },
            {
              "id": "vt7uesi87",
              "point": "Qualifying Nouns (Relative Clauses)",
              "meaning": "\"In Japanese, you can modify a noun with a verb phrase simply by placing the verb phrase *before* the noun. The verb MUST be in the Short Form. This acts like \"\"that\"\" or \"\"who\"\" clauses in English (e.g., \"\"The book THAT I bought\"\").\"",
              "sentences": "昨日買った本。<br>The book (that) I bought yesterday.<br><br>眼鏡をかけている人。<br>The person (who is) wearing glasses."
            },
            {
              "id": "vyar3adc9",
              "point": "Mada ~te imasen (Not yet)",
              "meaning": "\"To say you haven't done something yet, use \"\"Mada\"\" (not yet) with the \"\"Te-form + imasen\"\". This implies that the action is incomplete but expected to happen.\"",
              "sentences": "まだ食べていません。<br>I haven't eaten yet.<br><br>まだ宿題をしていません。<br>I haven't done my homework yet."
            },
            {
              "id": "q6uwy6rf9",
              "point": "~Kara (Reason / Because)",
              "meaning": "\"The particle \"\"kara\"\" means \"\"because\"\". It is placed at the end of the reason clause. Structure: [Reason] kara, [Result]. It creates a clear cause-and-effect relationship.\"",
              "sentences": "忙しかったから、パーティーに行きませんでした。<br>Because I was busy, I didn't go to the party.<br><br>暑かったから、水を飲みました。<br>Because it was hot, I drank water."
            }
          ],
          "genki1_10": [
            {
              "id": "6yy2p3sqh",
              "point": "Comparison (A no hou ga...)",
              "meaning": "\"To compare two things (A is more X than B), use the pattern: \"\"A no hou ga B yori (Property)\"\". \"\"No hou ga\"\" marks the winner (more), and \"\"yori\"\" marks the standard (than).\"",
              "sentences": "長野のほうが福岡より寒いです。<br>Nagano is colder than Fukuoka.<br><br>味噌のほうが醤油よりおいしいです。<br>Miso is tastier than Shoyu."
            },
            {
              "id": "71ibpfkiv",
              "point": "Asking Comparison (Docchi no hou ga...)",
              "meaning": "\"To ask \"\"Which is more...?\"\", use \"\"Docchi/Dochira no hou ga...\"\". You list the options with \"\"to\"\" (A to B to...). Note that you generally do not use \"\"yori\"\" in the question, just \"\"no hou ga\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "漫画とアニメと、どっちのほうが面白いですか。<br>Which is more interesting, manga or anime?"
            },
            {
              "id": "5aawlmu3j",
              "point": "Superlative (Ichiban)",
              "meaning": "\"To say \"\"the most / the best\"\" among a group of three or more, use the structure: [Group] no naka de [Item] ga ichiban [Property]. \"\"No naka de\"\" means \"\"among/inside\"\". \"\"Ichiban\"\" means \"\"number one\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "ラーメンの中で、とんこつが一番好きです。<br>Among ramen, I like Tonkotsu the best.<br><br>アニメの中で、何が一番面白いですか。<br>Among anime, what is the most interesting?"
            },
            {
              "id": "zgyv5y6l3",
              "point": "Adjective/Noun + No (Replacement)",
              "meaning": "\"The particle \"\"no\"\" can replace a noun to avoid repetition, functioning like \"\"one\"\" in English (e.g., \"\"The red one\"\"). It replaces the noun modified by an adjective or another noun.\"",
              "sentences": "これは私のペンです。それはメアリーさんのです。<br>This is my pen. That is Mary's (one).<br><br>一番大きいのをください。<br>Please give me the biggest one."
            },
            {
              "id": "3p1v8lf43",
              "point": "~Tsumori (Intention)",
              "meaning": "\"Use \"\"Verb (Dictionary form) + tsumori\"\" to express a plan or intention (\"\"I plan to...\"\"). To express \"\"plan not to\"\", use \"\"Verb (Nai-form) + tsumori\"\". It implies a firmer plan than just \"\"tai\"\" (want).\"",
              "sentences": "週末、京都に行くつもりです。<br>I plan to go to Kyoto this weekend.<br><br>明日は出かけないつもりです。<br>I plan not to go out tomorrow."
            },
            {
              "id": "crc5kodqb",
              "point": "~Naru (To Become)",
              "meaning": "\"To express a change of state (\"\"become\"\"), use \"\"~naru\"\". I-adjectives: drop \"\"i\"\" + \"\"ku naru\"\". Na-adjectives/Nouns: add \"\"ni naru\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "楽しくなる。<br>To become fun.<br><br>きれいになる。<br>To become pretty.<br><br>医者になる。<br>To become a doctor."
            },
            {
              "id": "jm2bmt503",
              "point": "Dokoka / Dokonimo (Some/Nowhere)",
              "meaning": "\"Dokoka means \"\"somewhere\"\". \"\"Dokonimo\"\" means \"\"nowhere\"\" (and must be used with a negative verb). Particles like \"\"ni\"\" or \"\"he\"\" can be inserted or omitted depending on the verb, but \"\"mo\"\" is essential for the negative meaning.\"",
              "sentences": "どこかへ行きたいです。<br>I want to go somewhere.<br><br>どこにも行きませんでした。<br>I didn't go anywhere."
            },
            {
              "id": "rfg2e5aor",
              "point": "Particle De (Means/Method)",
              "meaning": "\"The particle \"\"de\"\" indicates the tool, method, or means of transportation used to do an action. It answers \"\"How?\"\" or \"\"With what?\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "バスで行きます。<br>I will go by bus.<br><br>箸で食べます。<br>I eat with chopsticks.<br><br>日本語で話します。<br>I speak in Japanese."
            }
          ],
          "genki1_11": [
            {
              "id": "eoixsbgp4",
              "point": "~Tai (Desire)",
              "meaning": "\"To express \"\"I want to...\"\", use the verb stem + \"\"tai\"\". This form conjugates exactly like an I-adjective (Tai, Takunai, Takatta). The object can be marked with \"\"ga\"\" or \"\"o\"\", though \"\"ga\"\" emphasizes the object more.\"",
              "sentences": "水が飲みたいです。<br>I want to drink water.<br><br>本を買いたいです。<br>I want to buy a book."
            },
            {
              "id": "phapgoksl",
              "point": "~Tari ~Tari (Representative Listing)",
              "meaning": "\"To list actions as examples (implies \"\"and so on\"\"), use the Ta-form + ri. The structure is \"\"V1-tari V2-tari suru\"\". The final \"\"suru\"\" determines the tense of the sentence.\"",
              "sentences": "週末は、本を読んだり、寝たりしました。<br>On the weekend, I read books, slept, and so on.<br><br>歌ったり、踊ったりします。<br>We sing, dance, etc."
            },
            {
              "id": "0ajpsirvc",
              "point": "~Ta koto ga aru (Experience)",
              "meaning": "\"To say \"\"I have done X before\"\", use the Past Tense (Ta-form) + \"\"koto ga aru\"\". This speaks about life experience rather than a specific past event.\"",
              "sentences": "沖縄に行ったことがあります。<br>I have been to Okinawa before.<br><br>納豆を食べたことがないです。<br>I have never eaten natto."
            },
            {
              "id": "12vid2h0x",
              "point": "Noun ~Ya (Partial List)",
              "meaning": "\"The particle \"\"ya\"\" connects nouns like \"\"to\"\" (and), but implies the list is incomplete (\"\"A, B, and so on\"\"). It hints that there are other items not mentioned.\"",
              "sentences": "猫や犬がいます。<br>There are cats, dogs, and others.<br><br>ピカチュウやポッチャマが好きです。<br>I like Pikachu, Piplup, etc."
            }
          ],
          "genki1_12": [
            {
              "id": "6mpsrsrq6",
              "point": "~Ndesu (Explanatory)",
              "meaning": "\"The \"\"~ndesu\"\" (or \"\"~n desu\"\") ending adds an explanatory tone to a statement. It is used to explain a reason, provide background information, or ask for an explanation (\"\"Why?\"\"). It is softer and more conversational than just stating facts. In writing, it becomes \"\"~no desu\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "どうしたんですか。<br>What is the matter? (Seeking explanation)<br><br>頭が痛いんです。<br>(It's that) My head hurts.<br><br>明日テストがあるんです。<br>(The reason is that) I have a test tomorrow."
            },
            {
              "id": "7ha28isgz",
              "point": "~Sugiru (Too much)",
              "meaning": "\"To express that something is excessive (\"\"too much\"\" or \"\"too [adjective]\"\"), attach \"\"~sugiru\"\" to the stem. It often implies a negative nuance (excessive to a fault). \"\"~Sugiru\"\" conjugates as a Ru-verb.\"",
              "sentences": "食べすぎました。<br>I ate too much.<br><br>このシャツは大きすぎます。<br>This shirt is too big.<br><br>複雑すぎます。<br>It is too complicated."
            },
            {
              "id": "davt91v4p",
              "point": "~Hou ga ii (Advice)",
              "meaning": "\"To give advice (\"\"You had better...\"\"), use \"\"~hou ga ii\"\". Note the specific conjugation: For positive advice, use the **Past Tense (Ta-form)**. For negative advice, use the **Present Negative (Nai-form)**. It can sound strong, so use it carefully with superiors.\"",
              "sentences": "野菜を食べたほうがいいです。<br>You should eat vegetables.<br><br>タバコを吸わないほうがいいです。<br>You had better not smoke."
            },
            {
              "id": "zlgkv4v8x",
              "point": "~Node (Reason)",
              "meaning": "\"Like \"\"kara\"\", \"\"~node\"\" means \"\"because\"\" or \"\"since\"\". However, \"\"~node\"\" sounds more objective, polite, and formal. It explains a cause gently. For Na-adjectives and Nouns, you must add \"\"na\"\" before \"\"node\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "今日は日曜日なので、銀行は休みです。<br>Since today is Sunday, the bank is closed.<br><br>寒いので、出かけません。<br>Because it is cold, I won't go out."
            },
            {
              "id": "xppn6dlxn",
              "point": "~Nakya ikemasen (Obligation)",
              "meaning": "\"This means \"\"must do\"\" or \"\"have to do\"\". It is a contraction of \"\"~nakereba ikemasen\"\". It expresses obligation or duty.\"",
              "sentences": "勉強しなきゃいけません。<br>I must study.<br><br>薬を飲まなきゃいけません。<br>I have to take medicine."
            },
            {
              "id": "5fyg9ykfz",
              "point": "~Deshou (Prediction)",
              "meaning": "\"Use \"\"~deshou\"\" to express a prediction, probability, or guess (\"\"probably\"\"). It conveys that the speaker is not 100% sure but thinks it is likely. It is also used to ask for agreement (\"\"Right?\"\").\"",
              "sentences": "明日は雨でしょう。<br>It will probably rain tomorrow.<br><br>その本は高いでしょう。<br>That book is probably expensive."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_13": [
            {
              "id": "fj75izmdn",
              "point": "Potential Form (Can do)",
              "meaning": "\"The potential form expresses the ability to do something (\"\"can do\"\"). Godan verbs change the final \"\"u\"\" sound to \"\"eru\"\". Ichidan verbs drop \"\"ru\"\" and add \"\"rareru\"\" (though \"\"reru\"\" is common in speech). Irregular verbs are \"\"dekiru\"\" (suru) and \"\"korareru\"\" (kuru). [cite_start]Use the particle \"\"ga\"\" to mark the object able to be done[cite: 1522].\"",
              "sentences": "ラーメンが食べられます。<br>I can eat ramen.<br><br>日本語が話せます。<br>I can speak Japanese.<br><br>漢字が読めます。<br>I can read kanji."
            },
            {
              "id": "khlvyacch",
              "point": "~Shi ~Shi (Listing Reasons)",
              "meaning": "\"This structure lists multiple reasons or facts for a situation implying \"\"and besides\"\" or \"\"not only this but also that\"\". It attaches to the short form. [cite_start]For Nouns and Na-adjectives \"\"da\"\" is required before \"\"shi\"\"[cite: 1529].\"",
              "sentences": "この店は安いし、美味しいです。<br>This shop is cheap and delicious.<br><br>彼女は親切だし、きれいです。<br>She is kind and pretty.<br><br>天気がいいし、出かけましょう。<br>The weather is nice so let's go out."
            },
            {
              "id": "g2kgf4kks",
              "point": "~Te miru (Trying)",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses trying an action to see what the result will be (\"\"try doing\"\"). Attach \"\"miru\"\" to the Te-form of the verb. [cite_start]\"\"Miru\"\" conjugates as an Ichidan verb[cite: 1536].\"",
              "sentences": "新しい料理を作ってみました。<br>I tried making a new dish.<br><br>温泉に行ってみましたか。<br>Did you try going to a hot spring?<br><br>映画を見てみます。<br>I'll try watching the movie."
            },
            {
              "id": "i419kq9zx",
              "point": "~Sou (Visual Appearance)",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses that something \"\"looks like\"\" or \"\"seems\"\" based on visual appearance. For verbs use the Masu-stem + sou. For I-adjectives drop \"\"i\"\" + sou. For Na-adjectives attach directly. [cite_start]\"\"Ii\"\" (good) becomes \"\"yosasou\"\"[cite: 1542].\"",
              "sentences": "雨が降りそうです。<br>It looks like it will rain.<br><br>このケーキは美味しそうです。<br>This cake looks delicious.<br><br>暑そうです。<br>It looks hot."
            },
            {
              "id": "c7ts1b2t7",
              "point": "~Nara (Contextual Conditional)",
              "meaning": "\"This conditional means \"\"if that is the case\"\" or \"\"if it is [Topic]\"\". It is used to give advice or recommendations based on something mentioned by the other person. [cite_start]It attaches directly to the word[cite: 1549].\"",
              "sentences": "日本なら、ラーメンを食べてみて下さい。<br>If it's Japan we're talking about please try eating ramen.<br><br>時間があるなら、映画を見ましょう。<br>If you have time let's watch a movie.<br><br>日本語なら、問題ありません。<br>If it's Japanese there's no problem."
            },
            {
              "id": "6mxm91akx",
              "point": "Frequency per Period",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses how often an action happens within a set time frame. The structure is [Period] \"\"ni\"\" [Frequency]. [cite_start]The particle \"\"ni\"\" is essential to mark the span of time[cite: 1557].\"",
              "sentences": "一日に一回、コーヒーを飲みます。<br>I drink coffee once a day.<br><br>一週間に三回運動します。<br>I exercise three times a week.<br><br>毎朝ジョギングします。<br>I jog every morning."
            },
            {
              "id": "495wd4vw8",
              "point": "Adjective to Adverb",
              "meaning": "\"To turn an I-adjective into an adverb (to modify a verb) drop the final \"\"i\"\" and add \"\"ku\"\". [cite_start]For Na-adjectives add \"\"ni\"\"[cite: 1563].\"",
              "sentences": "速く走ります。<br>I run fast.<br><br>静かに話してください。<br>Please speak quietly.<br><br>楽しく遊んでいます。<br>They are playing happily."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_14": [
            {
              "id": "o706p21zp",
              "point": "~Hoshii (Desire for Noun)",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses \"\"I want [Noun]\"\". It conjugates exactly like an I-adjective. The object wanted is marked with \"\"ga\"\" (subject) rather than \"\"o\"\". [cite_start]This form is only used for the speaker's desires[cite: 1576].\"",
              "sentences": "新しい靴がほしい。<br>I want new shoes.<br><br>りんごがほしくなかった。<br>I didn't want an apple."
            },
            {
              "id": "nr0ptsqvk",
              "point": "~Garu (Third Person Desire)",
              "meaning": "\"Used to describe someone else's desire or emotion since you cannot feel their feelings directly. \"\"Hoshigaru\"\" (they want a noun) or \"\"Tagaru\"\" (they want to do). [cite_start]It usually takes the continuous form \"\"gatteiru\"\"[cite: 1582].\"",
              "sentences": "子どもはおもちゃをほしがっている。<br>The child seems to want a toy.<br><br>彼は日本へ行きたがっています。<br>He wants to go to Japan."
            },
            {
              "id": "mmxt5bnqx",
              "point": "Giving and Receiving",
              "meaning": "Ageru (I give to others / Someone gives to others). Kureru (Someone gives to me). Morau (I receive from someone). [cite_start]The choice depends on the direction of the item relative to the speaker[cite: 1588].",
              "sentences": "僕は雪にプレゼントをあげた。<br>I gave Yuki a present.<br><br>雪は僕にお茶をくれた。<br>Yuki gave me tea.<br><br>僕は雪から本をもらった。<br>I received a book from Yuki."
            },
            {
              "id": "j2j78jpad",
              "point": "~Tara dou desu ka (Advice)",
              "meaning": "\"Offers advice or a suggestion meaning \"\"Why don't you...\"\" or \"\"How about...\"\". [cite_start]It attaches to the Past (Ta) form of the verb + \"\"ra dou desu ka\"\"[cite: 1599].\"",
              "sentences": "もっと寝たらどうですか。<br>Why don't you sleep a little more?<br><br>みんなからお金をもらったらどうですか。<br>Why don't you get money from everyone?"
            },
            {
              "id": "betibfrzu",
              "point": "~Kamo shirenai (Possibility)",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses uncertainty or possibility meaning \"\"might\"\" or \"\"maybe\"\". It follows the Short Form of verbs adjectives and nouns. [cite_start]For Na-adj and Nouns do not add \"\"da\"\"[cite: 1606].\"",
              "sentences": "雨が降るかもしれない。<br>It might rain.<br><br>先生だったかもしれません。<br>It might have been the teacher."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_15": [
            {
              "id": "pv68og1cj",
              "point": "Volitional Form (Casual Let's)",
              "meaning": "\"The Volitional form is the casual version of \"\"~mashou\"\" (Let's). Godan verbs: change \"\"u\"\" to \"\"ou\"\". Ichidan verbs: drop \"\"ru\"\" add \"\"you\"\". [cite_start]Irregular: Suru->Shiyou Kuru->Koyou[cite: 1618].\"",
              "sentences": "ラーメンを食べに行こう。<br>Let's go eat ramen.<br><br>泳ぎに行こうか。<br>Shall we go swimming?"
            },
            {
              "id": "30pzifstn",
              "point": "Volitional + To Omou (Intention)",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses intention. \"\"~to omoimasu\"\" indicates a decision made on the spot (\"\"I think I will...\"\"). [cite_start]\"\"~to omotteimasu\"\" indicates a decision already made (\"\"I've been thinking of...\"\").[cite: 1623].\"",
              "sentences": "新しいのを買おうと思っています。<br>I intend to buy a new one.<br><br>調べようと思います。<br>I think I will look into it."
            },
            {
              "id": "coyrcqoky",
              "point": "~Te oku (Preparation)",
              "meaning": "\"Means to do something in advance for future convenience. \"\"Te-form + oku\"\". [cite_start]In casual speech it often contracts to \"\"~toku\"\" (e.g. \"\"shitoku\"\")[cite: 1629].\"",
              "sentences": "パーティーのためにビールを買っておこう。<br>Let's buy beer in preparation for the party.<br><br>宿題を早くしておいた。<br>I did my homework early (in advance)."
            },
            {
              "id": "94ey2dsv6",
              "point": "Qualifying Nouns with Sentences",
              "meaning": "You can modify a noun with a full sentence. The modifying sentence must use the Short Form. [cite_start]It comes *before* the noun it describes.[cite: 1635].",
              "sentences": "父が作ったケーキ。<br>The cake my dad made.<br><br>日本に住んでいる友達。<br>A friend who lives in Japan.<br><br>昨日借りた本。<br>The book I borrowed yesterday."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_16": [
            {
              "id": "n6woyh8kz",
              "point": "Giving Services (~te ageru/kureru/morau)",
              "meaning": "\"These helping verbs describe who benefits from an action. \"\"~te ageru\"\" means you do something for someone else. \"\"~te kureru\"\" means someone does something for you (or your in-group). \"\"~te morau\"\" means you get someone to do something for you. The choice depends on the direction of the favor.\"",
              "sentences": "友達に昼ご飯を作ってあげました。<br>I made lunch for my friend.<br><br>友達が昼ご飯を作ってくれました。<br>My friend made lunch for me.<br><br>友達に昼ご飯を作ってもらいました。<br>I got my friend to make lunch for me."
            },
            {
              "id": "pe6uczcfq",
              "point": "Polite Requests (~te itadakemasenka)",
              "meaning": "\"To make a request more polite than \"\"~te kudasai\"\", use these forms. \"\"~te itadakemasenka\"\" is very polite (would you be so kind as to...). \"\"~te kuremasenka\"\" is polite (would you...). \"\"~te kurenai\"\" is casual (will you...).\"",
              "sentences": "この漢字を読んでいただけませんか。<br>Would you be so kind as to read this kanji?<br><br>ちょっと手伝ってくれませんか。<br>Would you help me for a moment?<br><br>それ、取ってくれない？<br>Will you pass me that?"
            },
            {
              "id": "r4k5mma29",
              "point": "Hopes and Wishes (~to ii desu)",
              "meaning": "\"To express a hope, use the Present Short form + \"\"to ii desu\"\". Use \"\"~to ii desu ne\"\" when wishing for someone else's good fortune. Use \"\"~to ii n desu ga\"\" when wishing for your own good fortune (it softens the wish).\"",
              "sentences": "あした晴れるといいですね。<br>I hope it will be sunny tomorrow (for you).<br><br>試験に受かるといいんですが。<br>I hope I pass the exam."
            },
            {
              "id": "apz48gzgk",
              "point": "Time Clauses (~toki)",
              "meaning": "\"The particle \"\"toki\"\" means \"\"when\"\" or \"\"at the time of\"\". The tense of the verb BEFORE \"\"toki\"\" is crucial. If it is Present Tense (Dictionary form), the main action happens *before* the \"\"toki\"\" action completes. If it is Past Tense (Ta-form), the main action happens *after* the \"\"toki\"\" action is finished.\"",
              "sentences": "日本に行く時、カメラを買いました。<br>I bought a camera when I went to Japan (Bought it before leaving or on the way).<br><br>日本に行った時、カメラを買いました。<br>I bought a camera when I went to Japan (Bought it after arriving there)."
            },
            {
              "id": "oyaupyd2k",
              "point": "Apologizing (~te sumimasen)",
              "meaning": "\"To apologize for something you did, use \"\"Te-form + sumimasen deshita\"\". To apologize for something you failed to do, use \"\"Nakute (negative te-form) + sumimasen deshita\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "汚してすみませんでした。<br>I am sorry for making it dirty.<br><br>宿題を忘れてすみませんでした。<br>I am sorry for forgetting homework.<br><br>行けなくてすみません。<br>I am sorry I cannot go."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_17": [
            {
              "id": "c2ompzmf6",
              "point": "~Sou desu (Hearsay)",
              "meaning": "\"This form expresses \"\"I hear that...\"\" or \"\"It is said that...\"\". It attaches to the **Short Form** of verbs, adjectives, and nouns. Unlike the appearance \"\"sou\"\" (stem + sou), this one preserves the final sounds (like \"\"i\"\" or \"\"u\"\").\"",
              "sentences": "明日は雨だそうです。<br>I heard that it will rain tomorrow.<br><br>そのクラスは難しいそうです。<br>I heard that class is difficult.<br><br>メアリーさんは肉を食べないそうです。<br>I heard Mary doesn't eat meat."
            },
            {
              "id": "dwi3i58s5",
              "point": "~Tte (Casual Quote)",
              "meaning": "\"In informal speech, \"\"to itte imashita\"\" (they said) or \"\"sou desu\"\" (I heard) is often replaced by \"\"tte\"\". It can quote words directly or report what you heard. It attaches to the end of the sentence.\"",
              "sentences": "明日はテストだって。<br>(I heard/They said) There is a test tomorrow.<br><br>なんて言った？<br>What did he say?<br><br>田中さんは来ないって。<br>Tanaka-san said he isn't coming."
            },
            {
              "id": "bvfl9oanb",
              "point": "~Tara (Conditional)",
              "meaning": "\"The conditional \"\"~tara\"\" means \"\"if\"\" or \"\"when\"\". It is formed by adding \"\"ra\"\" to the Past Tense (Ta-form). It emphasizes the sequence: \"\"Once A happens, then B\"\". It is the most versatile conditional for \"\"if/when\"\" situations.\"",
              "sentences": "雨が降ったら、行きません。<br>If it rains, I won't go.<br><br>日本に行ったら、着物を買いたいです。<br>If/When I go to Japan, I want to buy a kimono."
            },
            {
              "id": "cy6gplqsv",
              "point": "~Nakutemo ii desu (No Obligation)",
              "meaning": "\"To say \"\"you do not have to do...\"\", use the negative te-form but drop the \"\"te\"\" and add \"\"kutemo ii desu\"\". It literally means \"\"even if you don't X, it is good\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "靴を脱がなくてもいいです。<br>You don't have to take off your shoes.<br><br>今日は払わなくてもいいですよ。<br>You don't have to pay today."
            },
            {
              "id": "4b99d0s9k",
              "point": "~Mitai desu (Resemblance)",
              "meaning": "\"To say something \"\"looks like\"\" or \"\"resembles\"\" a noun, use \"\"Noun + mitai desu\"\". It can also follow verbs to mean \"\"it looks like someone did X\"\". It is slightly more casual than \"\"you desu\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "私のお父さんはゴリラみたいです。<br>My father looks like a gorilla.<br><br>雨が降ったみたいです。<br>It looks like it rained (judging by puddles)."
            },
            {
              "id": "71tgp9a3n",
              "point": "Before and After (~Mae ni / ~Te kara)",
              "meaning": "\"To express sequence clearly: Use \"\"Verb Dictionary Form + mae ni\"\" for \"\"Before doing X\"\". Use \"\"Verb Te-form + kara\"\" for \"\"After doing X\"\" (implying immediately after or as a prerequisite).\"",
              "sentences": "寝る前に歯を磨きます。<br>I brush my teeth before I sleep.<br><br>勉強してから、遊びに行きました。<br>I went to hang out after I studied."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_18": [
            {
              "id": "a8d9bza2k",
              "point": "Transitivity Pairs (Jidoushi / Tadoushi)",
              "meaning": "Japanese verbs often come in pairs: Transitive (Tadoushi) where someone does something to an object (marked by 'o'), and Intransitive (Jidoushi) where something happens naturally (marked by 'ga').",
              "sentences": "ドアを開けました。<br>I opened the door. (Transitive)<br><br>ドアが開きました。<br>The door opened. (Intransitive)<br><br>電気を消しました。<br>I turned off the light. (Transitive)<br><br>電気が消えました。<br>The light went off. (Intransitive)"
            },
            {
              "id": "xg68hq2lu",
              "point": "Resultant State (~Te iru + Intransitive)",
              "meaning": "\"When \"\"~te iru\"\" is used with Intransitive verbs describing a change (like open, break, fall), it indicates a *Resultant State*. \"\"Mado ga aiteiru\"\" means \"\"The window is open\"\" (it opened and remains open), NOT \"\"The window is currently opening\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "窓が開いています。<br>The window is open.<br><br>電気がついています。<br>The light is on.<br><br>車が壊れています。<br>The car is broken."
            },
            {
              "id": "ff0c89xjk",
              "point": "~Te shimau (Completion / Regret)",
              "meaning": "\"This form has two nuances. 1. Completion: \"\"Finished doing X completely\"\". 2. Regret: \"\"Did X (accidentally/unfortunately)\"\". In speech, \"\"~te shimau\"\" contracts to \"\"~chau\"\" and \"\"~de shimau\"\" to \"\"~jau\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "本を読んでしまいました。<br>I finished reading the book completely.<br><br>電車の中に鞄を忘れてしまいました。<br>I inadvertently left my bag on the train.<br><br>食べちゃった。<br>I ate it (oops/finished it)."
            },
            {
              "id": "czt66lx0s",
              "point": "Conditional ~To (Natural Consequence)",
              "meaning": "\"The particle \"\"to\"\" creates a conditional \"\"Whenever A happens, B happens\"\". It is used for natural laws, machine functions, or habitual events. It cannot be used for requests or volitional acts.\"",
              "sentences": "このボタンを押すと、切符が出ます。<br>If/When you press this button, a ticket comes out.<br><br>春になると、桜が咲きます。<br>When spring comes, cherry blossoms bloom."
            },
            {
              "id": "12ekkvg2a",
              "point": "Simultaneous Actions (~Nagara)",
              "meaning": "\"To describe doing two things at the same time, use the Verb Stem + \"\"nagara\"\". The main action is the second verb.\"",
              "sentences": "音楽を聞きながら、勉強します。<br>I study while listening to music.<br><br>働きながら、日本語を勉強しています。<br>I am studying Japanese while working."
            },
            {
              "id": "1rkoea8ms",
              "point": "~Ba yokatta (Regret)",
              "meaning": "\"To express \"\"I should have done...\"\", use the \"\"Ba-form\"\" + \"\"yokatta\"\" (literally: If I had done X, it would have been good). For negative (\"\"should not have\"\"), use \"\"Nakereba yokatta\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "もっと勉強すればよかったです。<br>I should have studied more.<br><br>あんなこと言わなければよかったです。<br>I shouldn't have said such a thing."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_19": [
            {
              "id": "8gwq4xxu0",
              "point": "Honorific Verbs (Keigo)",
              "meaning": "Honorific verbs (Sonkeigo) are used to describe the actions of someone you respect (superiors, customers, teachers). You never use them for yourself. They replace standard verbs with special vocabulary to elevate the subject.",
              "sentences": "先生は明日いらっしゃいますか。<br>Will the teacher be here tomorrow?<br><br>どうぞ召し上がってください。<br>Please eat.<br><br>社長はそうおっしゃいました。<br>The company president said so."
            },
            {
              "id": "vf1k2cth0",
              "point": "General Honorifics (O...ni naru)",
              "meaning": "\"If a verb does not have a special honorific form, use the pattern \"\"O + Verb Stem + ni naru\"\". This raises the status of the person doing the action. For Sino-Japanese words (suru-verbs), use \"\"Go + Noun + ni naru\"\" (though this is rarer than the \"\"suru\"\" humble form).\"",
              "sentences": "先生は本をお読みになります。<br>The teacher reads a book.<br><br>切符をお持ちですか。<br>Do you have a ticket?<br><br>社長は帰られました。<br>The president went home (Passive honorific)."
            },
            {
              "id": "or05o68vt",
              "point": "Respectful Commands (O...kudasai)",
              "meaning": "\"To give a polite instruction or command (often used in customer service), use \"\"O + Verb Stem + kudasai\"\". For Sino-Japanese words, use \"\"Go + Noun + kudasai\"\". It is extremely polite but still a command.\"",
              "sentences": "少々お待ちください。<br>Please wait a moment.<br><br>ご注意ください。<br>Please be careful.<br><br>こちらにお座りください。<br>Please sit here."
            },
            {
              "id": "ftnrww8ks",
              "point": "Thanking (~Te kurete)",
              "meaning": "\"To thank someone for a specific action, use the Te-form + \"\"arigatou\"\". Use \"\"~te kurete arigatou\"\" for friends. Use \"\"~teくださって arigatou gozaimasu\"\" for superiors (honorific version of kureru).\"",
              "sentences": "手伝ってくれてありがとう。<br>Thanks for helping me.<br><br>来てくださってありがとうございました。<br>Thank you very much for coming (to a superior).<br><br>プレゼントをくださってありがとうございます。<br>Thank you for giving me a present."
            },
            {
              "id": "sy09qq4q5",
              "point": "~Te yokatta (Glad I did)",
              "meaning": "\"To express relief or happiness that something happened, use the Te-form + \"\"yokatta\"\" (\"\"It was good that...\"\"). To express relief that something did NOT happen, use the Negative Te-form (Nakute) + \"\"yokatta\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "日本に行ってよかったです。<br>I am glad I went to Japan.<br><br>雨が降らなくてよかったです。<br>I am glad it did not rain.<br><br>その本を買わなくてよかったです。<br>I am glad I didn't buy that book."
            },
            {
              "id": "69uzv0bip",
              "point": "~Hazu desu (Expectation)",
              "meaning": "\"Use \"\"~hazu desu\"\" to express a strong expectation based on facts or logic (\"\"It is supposed to...\"\" or \"\"I expect that...\"\"). It implies you have a reason to believe it. It attaches to the Short Form (Nouns use 'no', Na-adj use 'na').\"",
              "sentences": "彼は来るはずです。<br>He is supposed to come (e.g., he said he would).<br><br>この本は面白いはずです。<br>This book should be interesting (e.g., it is a best-seller).<br><br>今日は日曜日のはずです。<br>It should be Sunday today."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_20": [
            {
              "id": "amb5kebi0",
              "point": "Humble Verbs (Kenjougo)",
              "meaning": "Humble verbs are used when speaking about YOUR actions (or your group's) to someone superior. They lower your status to show respect to the listener. Standard verbs are replaced by special vocabulary.",
              "sentences": "私はパウと申します。<br>My name is Pau (I am called Pau).<br><br>明日、会社に参ります。<br>I will go to the company tomorrow.<br><br>お荷物をお持ちします。<br>I will carry your bag."
            },
            {
              "id": "jheamyeyl",
              "point": "General Humble (O...suru)",
              "meaning": "\"If a verb lacks a special humble form, use \"\"O + Stem + suru\"\" (or \"\"itasu\"\" for extra humbleness). For Sino-Japanese verbs, use \"\"Go + Noun + suru/itasu\"\". This implies you are doing the action *for* the listener or it affects them.\"",
              "sentences": "先生、お手伝いします。<br>Professor, I will help you.<br><br>後でご説明します。<br>I will explain later.<br><br>駅までお送りします。<br>I will drive/send you to the station."
            },
            {
              "id": "hxpnlsk4u",
              "point": "~Naide (Without doing)",
              "meaning": "\"To say you did one thing *without* doing another, use \"\"Negative Short Form + de\"\". It connects two actions where the first one is absent.\"",
              "sentences": "寝ないで勉強しました。<br>I studied without sleeping.<br><br>辞書を使わないで新聞を読みます。<br>I read the newspaper without using a dictionary.<br><br>朝ごはんを食べないで学校に来ました。<br>I came to school without eating breakfast."
            },
            {
              "id": "7gfe496yl",
              "point": "Embedded Questions (~Ka)",
              "meaning": "\"To include a question (Who, What, Where) inside a larger sentence, use the Short Form + \"\"ka\"\". It functions like a noun clause. For Na-adj/Nouns, remove \"\"da\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "誰が一番頭がいいか知っていますか。<br>Do you know who is the smartest?<br><br>プレゼントに何がいいかわかりません。<br>I don't know what is good for a present."
            },
            {
              "id": "fbqibh3eo",
              "point": "Embedded Yes/No (~Ka dou ka)",
              "meaning": "\"To include a Yes/No question inside a sentence (e.g., \"\"I don't know IF...\"\"), use \"\"Short Form + ka dou ka\"\". This means \"\"whether or not\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "間違いがないかどうか調べてください。<br>Please check whether there are errors or not.<br><br>あの人が学生かどうかわかりません。<br>I don't know if that person is a student."
            },
            {
              "id": "xhukd84ae",
              "point": "~To iu (Called...)",
              "meaning": "\"To define a name or title, use \"\"Name + to iu + Noun\"\". It translates to \"\"A [Noun] called [Name]\"\". It introduces proper nouns or unfamiliar terms.\"",
              "sentences": "\"ポチという犬を飼っています。<br>I have a dog called Pochi.<br><br>花子さんという人を知っていますか。<br>Do you know a person called Hanako?<br><br>「君の名は」という映画を見ました。<br>I watched a movie called \"\"Your Name\"\".\""
            },
            {
              "id": "q4e1fvekr",
              "point": "~Yasui / ~Nikui (Easy/Hard)",
              "meaning": "\"To say something is easy or difficult to do, attach \"\"~yasui\"\" (easy) or \"\"~nikui\"\" (hard) to the Verb Stem. The result conjugates exactly like an I-adjective.\"",
              "sentences": "この電子辞書は使いやすいです。<br>This electronic dictionary is easy to use.<br><br>骨が多い魚は食べにくいです。<br>Fish with many bones are hard to eat.<br><br>このグラスは割れにくいです。<br>This glass is hard to break."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_21": [
            {
              "id": "4jqj15y2x",
              "point": "Passive Form (Rareru)",
              "meaning": "\"The passive voice emphasizes the person receiving the action. The \"\"victim\"\" is marked by \"\"wa\"\", and the \"\"villain\"\" (doer) is marked by \"\"ni\"\". Ru-verbs: drop ru + rareru. U-verbs: a-sound + reru. It often implies the subject is negatively affected (suffering passive).\"",
              "sentences": "私は泥棒にお金を取られました。<br>I had my money taken by a thief.<br><br>雨に降られました。<br>I was rained on (and it was annoying).<br><br>褒められました。<br>I was praised."
            },
            {
              "id": "nhktnkqoi",
              "point": "~Te aru (Resultant State)",
              "meaning": "\"Describes a state resulting from an intentional action done by someone (usually for preparation). It implies \"\"It has been done\"\". Use \"\"Transitive Verb (Te-form) + aru\"\". The object is marked with \"\"ga\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "窓が開けてあります。<br>The window has been opened (by someone).<br><br>晩ご飯が作ってあります。<br>Dinner has been made (is ready)."
            },
            {
              "id": "gdawsh7kr",
              "point": "~Aida ni (During)",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses that an event happens *at some point* within a duration. Structure: \"\"State A (duration) + aida ni, Event B (moment)\"\". A usually takes \"\"~te iru\"\" or Noun + \"\"no\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "寝ている間に、地震がありました。<br>There was an earthquake while I was sleeping.<br><br>留守の間に友達が来ました。<br>A friend came while I was out."
            },
            {
              "id": "hhjlk5jye",
              "point": "Adjective + Suru (To make)",
              "meaning": "\"To describe changing the state of something (\"\"Make it clean\"\", \"\"Make it quiet\"\"), use Adjective + Suru. I-adj: drop \"\"i\"\" + \"\"ku suru\"\". Na-adj: add \"\"ni suru\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "音を大きくしました。<br>I made the volume louder.<br><br>部屋をきれいにしました。<br>I made the room clean.<br><br>静かにしてください。<br>Please be quiet (Make it quiet)."
            },
            {
              "id": "h0aihqo8k",
              "point": "~Te hoshii (Want you to do)",
              "meaning": "\"To express that you want *someone else* to do something, use \"\"Te-form + hoshii\"\". The person you want to do the action is marked with \"\"ni\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "私に英語を教えてほしいです。<br>I want you to teach me English.<br><br>父に長生きしてほしいです。<br>I want my father to live a long life."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_22": [
            {
              "id": "zhawgpoqw",
              "point": "Causative Form (Saseru)",
              "meaning": "\"The causative form expresses \"\"making\"\" or \"\"letting\"\" someone do something. The nuance (force vs. permission) depends on context. For transitive verbs, the actor is marked with \"\"ni\"\". For intransitive verbs, the actor is marked with \"\"ni\"\" (let) or \"\"o\"\" (make).\"",
              "sentences": "先生は学生に宿題をさせました。<br>The teacher made the students do homework.<br><br>母は私に部屋を掃除させました。<br>My mother made me clean my room.<br><br>子供にアイスを食べさせました。<br>I let my child eat ice cream."
            },
            {
              "id": "f93xfhn03",
              "point": "Causative + Giving (Permission)",
              "meaning": "\"To clearly express \"\"let someone do\"\" or \"\"allow someone to do\"\", use the Causative Te-form + \"\"ageru/kureru/morau\"\". \"\"Sasete ageru\"\" = I let him do it. \"\"Sasete kureru\"\" = He lets me do it. \"\"Sasete morau\"\" = I receive permission to do it.\"",
              "sentences": "先生は質問させてくれました。<br>The teacher let me ask a question.<br><br>貧乏だったので、両親は私を働かせてくれました。<br>Because we were poor, my parents allowed me to work.<br><br>今日は休ませてください。<br>Please let me rest today."
            },
            {
              "id": "lyp1e3fem",
              "point": "Command (~Nasai)",
              "meaning": "\"To give a firm instruction (from parent to child, or teacher to student), use \"\"Verb Stem + nasai\"\". It is authoritative but polite. It is softer than the imperative form but stronger than \"\"~te kudasai\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "野菜を食べなさい。<br>Eat your vegetables.<br><br>早く寝なさい。<br>Go to sleep early.<br><br>文句を言うのをやめなさい。<br>Stop complaining."
            },
            {
              "id": "0zg77m4sw",
              "point": "Imperative Form (Command/Prohibition)",
              "meaning": "\"The Imperative is a very strong, rough command (Do it!). The Negative Imperative is a strong prohibition (Don't do it!). These are used in emergencies, military contexts, or very rough male speech. \"\"Na\"\" attaches to the dictionary form for prohibition.\"",
              "sentences": "食べろ！<br>Eat it!<br><br>やめろ！<br>Stop it!<br><br>行くな！<br>Don't go!"
            },
            {
              "id": "n2jyhsk4b",
              "point": "~Ba (Conditional)",
              "meaning": "\"The \"\"~ba\"\" conditional expresses \"\"if\"\". It focuses on the condition itself: \"\"If A happens, then B\"\". It is good for general truths or hypothetical advice. Conjugation: Change \"\"u\"\" to \"\"e\"\" + \"\"ba\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "安ければ買います。<br>If it is cheap, I will buy it.<br><br>薬を飲めば治ります。<br>If you take medicine, you will get better.<br><br>行かなければ分かりません。<br>If you don't go, you won't know."
            },
            {
              "id": "5at10fyea",
              "point": "~Noni (Despite)",
              "meaning": "\"To express \"\"despite the fact that...\"\" or \"\"even though...\"\", use \"\"~noni\"\". It connects two contrasting ideas with a nuance of surprise or complaint. For Na-adjectives and Nouns, add \"\"na\"\" before \"\"noni\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "勉強したのに、悪い点を取ってしまいました。<br>Even though I studied, I got a bad grade.<br><br>日曜日なのに、働かなければいけません。<br>Even though it is Sunday, I have to work."
            },
            {
              "id": "nk3k4bksk",
              "point": "~No you ni (Like / As if)",
              "meaning": "\"To describe an action \"\"like X\"\", use \"\"Noun + no you ni\"\". To describe a noun \"\"like X\"\", use \"\"Noun + no you na + Noun\"\". It signifies resemblance.\"",
              "sentences": "魚のように泳げます。<br>I can swim like a fish.<br><br>ここは冷蔵庫のように寒いです。<br>It is cold like a fridge in here.<br><br>東京のような町が好きです。<br>I like towns like Tokyo."
            }
          ],
          "genki2_23": [
            {
              "id": "worqsvkny",
              "point": "Causative-Passive (Forced to)",
              "meaning": "\"To say \"\"I was made to do X (and I didn't want to)\"\", use the Causative-Passive. \"\"Saseru\"\" (Causative) + \"\"Rareru\"\" (Passive) = \"\"Saserareru\"\". For U-verbs ending in anything but 'su', this often contracts to \"\"asareru\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "母に野菜を食べさせられました。<br>I was made to eat vegetables by my mother.<br><br>歌を歌わされました。<br>I was forced to sing a song.<br><br>一時間待たされました。<br>I was made to wait for one hour."
            },
            {
              "id": "g88ondjjc",
              "point": "~Temo (Even if)",
              "meaning": "\"To say \"\"Even if X, Y\"\", use the Te-form + \"\"mo\"\". This expresses that the result Y will happen regardless of condition X.\"",
              "sentences": "雨が降っても、バーベキューをします。<br>Even if it rains, we will have a barbecue.<br><br>高くても、買いたいです。<br>Even if it is expensive, I want to buy it.<br><br>子供厚くてもわかります。<br>Even a child understands."
            },
            {
              "id": "3gd539huy",
              "point": "~Koto ni suru (Decide to)",
              "meaning": "\"To express a decision you just made (\"\"I decided to...\"\"), use \"\"Dictionary Form + koto ni suru\"\". It implies volitional choice.\"",
              "sentences": "車を買うことにしました。<br>I decided to buy a car.<br><br>もう彼に会わないことにしました。<br>I decided not to see him anymore."
            },
            {
              "id": "rqkrdu8qe",
              "point": "~Koto ni shite iru (Make it a rule)",
              "meaning": "\"To describe a habit or routine you have decided to keep, use the continuous form \"\"Koto ni shite iru\"\" (\"\"I make it a rule to...\"\").\"",
              "sentences": "毎日走ることにしています。<br>I make it a rule to run every day.<br><br>肉を食べないことにしています。<br>I make it a rule not to eat meat."
            },
            {
              "id": "64vp9cjix",
              "point": "~Made (Until)",
              "meaning": "\"To express \"\"until X happens\"\", use \"\"Verb Present Short + made\"\". Even if the sentence is past tense, the verb before \"\"made\"\" stays present.\"",
              "sentences": "晴れるまで喫茶店にいました。<br>I stayed at the cafe until it cleared up.<br><br>日本語が上手になるまで、国に帰りません。<br>I won't go back to my country until I become good at Japanese."
            },
            {
              "id": "om6o7opv2",
              "point": "~Kata (How to)",
              "meaning": "\"To say \"\"how to do X\"\", attach \"\"kata\"\" to the Verb Stem. The resulting word acts like a noun. The object particle \"\"o\"\" usually changes to \"\"no\"\".\"",
              "sentences": "漢字の読み方がわかりません。<br>I don't know how to read this kanji.<br><br>お箸の使い方を教えてください。<br>Please teach me how to use chopsticks."
            }
          ],
          "quartet1_1": [
            {
              "id": "x37apvfan",
              "point": "といえば",
              "meaning": "\"Used to pick up a topic mentioned in the conversation or a topic that is currently on your mind and expand on it, often to ask a question or provide a typical association. It translates to \"\"Speaking of...\"\" or \"\"If we are talking about...\"\"\"",
              "sentences": "お酒<b>といえば</b>、何が好き？<br>(Speaking of alcohol, what do you like?)<br><br>日本<b>といえば</b>、何が思いつきますか？<br>(Speaking of Japan, what comes to mind?)<br><br>安藤さん<b>といえば</b>、今日は来ないよね。<br>(Speaking of Ando-san, he isn't coming today, right?)"
            },
            {
              "id": "fpgsibcq2",
              "point": "なら",
              "meaning": "\"A contextual conditional meaning \"\"If that is the case\"\" or \"\"If it is true that...\"\" It is often used to give advice, suggestions, or requests based on what the other person just said or a specific situation.\"",
              "sentences": "日本に行く<b>なら</b>、ラーメンも食べてみてください。<br>(If you are going to Japan, please try eating ramen too.)<br><br>チーズ<b>なら</b>、二種類が売っています。<br>(If it's cheese you are looking for, they sell two kinds.)<br><br>来る<b>なら</b>、私は帰ろうかな。<br>(If he is coming, I think I might go home.)"
            },
            {
              "id": "zw31683un",
              "point": "とおり",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses that an action is done in the same way as something else, or that a result matches a prediction or plan. It translates to \"\"just as,\"\" \"\"exactly as,\"\" or \"\"in accordance with.\"\"\"",
              "sentences": "先生が言った<b>通り</b>に、勉強しました。<br>(I studied exactly as the teacher said.)<br><br>想像した<b>通り</b>、この公園は美しいですね。<br>(Just as I imagined, this park is beautiful, isn't it?)<br><br>計画<b>通り</b>、仕事がサクサク進んだ。<br>(Work proceeded smoothly, exactly as planned.)"
            },
            {
              "id": "txueywzqd",
              "point": "らしい",
              "meaning": "\"This grammar point has two distinct meanings.<br><br>Hearsay/Conjecture: \"\"It seems that...\"\" or \"\"I heard that...\"\" based on reliable information or observation.<br>Typical/Authentic: expressing that something strongly displays the characteristic \"\"essence\"\" of that noun (e.g., \"\"very man-like\"\").\"",
              "sentences": "\"明日の授業で映画を見る<b>らしい</b>。<br>(It seems we will watch a movie in tomorrow's class.)<br><br>結局、雨が降らない<b>らしい</b>。<br>(It seems it won't rain after all.)<br><br>このレストランは本当に日本<b>らしい</b>。<br>(This restaurant is truly authentic / very \"\"Japan-like\"\".)<br><br>子供<b>らしい</b>な。<br>(That is so child-like.)\""
            },
            {
              "id": "s7kyvsrl0",
              "point": "ために・ための",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses the purpose or objective of an action. It translates to \"\"in order to\"\" or \"\"for the purpose of.\"\" The subject of both clauses must be the same.\"",
              "sentences": "1. ラーメンを食べるために、日本へ行った。 (I went to Japan in order to eat ramen.)<br>2. アニメを見るために、ネットフリックスを買いたい。 (I want to buy Netflix in order to watch anime.)<br>3. これはラーメンを食べるためのスプーンです。 (This is a spoon for [the purpose of] eating ramen.)<br>4. 映画やテレビを見るためのサービスです。 (It is a service for watching movies and TV shows.)"
            },
            {
              "id": "33ut3vam8",
              "point": "がきっかけで",
              "meaning": "\"Indicates the initial reason, motivation, or specific event that triggered an action or change. It translates to \"\"with... as the start/cue\"\" or \"\"motivated by...\"\"\"",
              "sentences": "\"ブログ「Soul Beam」を読んだの<b>がきっかけで</b>、スペインに行きました。<br>(I went to Spain after being motivated by reading the blog \"\"Soul Beam\"\".)<br><br>新しい仕事を見つけたの<b>がきっかけで</b>、会社を辞めました。<br>(The cue for quitting my company was that I found a new job.)<br><br>BBQ<b>がきっかけで</b>、仲良くなりました。<br>(The initial reason we became friends was a BBQ.)\""
            },
            {
              "id": "cbwagnxr6",
              "point": "ようになる",
              "meaning": "Describes a change in state or habit. It indicates that someone has reached a point where they now do something they didn't do before, or have gained the ability to do something they couldn't do before.",
              "sentences": "ジムに通う<b>ようになった</b>。<br>(I started going to the gym regularly.)<br><br>毎日ゲームをする<b>ようになった</b>。<br>(I started playing games every day.)<br><br>筋トレができる<b>ようになった</b>。<br>(I became able to lift weights.)<br><br>思いついた曲が弾ける<b>ようになりたい</b>。<br>(I want to become able to play songs that come into my mind.)"
            },
            {
              "id": "w7t89b9ey",
              "point": "ようにする",
              "meaning": "Expresses a conscious effort to do (or not do) something. 〜ようにする indicates a future decision or general rule, while 〜ようにしている indicates a current, ongoing effort.",
              "sentences": "明日は早く着く<b>ようにする</b>よ。<br>(I'll make sure that I arrive early tomorrow.)<br><br>最近、毎晩八時間寝る<b>ようにしている</b>。<br>(Recently, I've been making an effort to sleep for eight hours every night.)<br><br>これからもっと飲む<b>ようにしたい</b>。<br>(From now on, I want to make it a point to drink more.)"
            },
            {
              "id": "2ni3xak3o",
              "point": "によると",
              "meaning": "Used to mark the source of information. It is almost always followed by a hearsay ending (like ～そうです or ～らしい) to indicate that the information is second-hand.",
              "sentences": "天気予報<b>によると</b>、明日は大雨になるそうです。<br>(According to the weather forecast, it appears that tomorrow will be heavy rain.)<br><br>安藤さんの話<b>によると</b>、彼はゆきさんに嫌われているらしい。<br>(According to Ando-san's story, he is hated by Yuki apparently.)<br><br>ゆき<b>によると</b>、これからもっと飲むようにしたいらしい。<br>(According to Yuki, apparently she wants to make it a point to drink more from now on.)"
            }
          ],
          "quartet1_2": [
            {
              "id": "nce83cxn0",
              "point": "～ずに / ～く",
              "meaning": "\"This form is used to connect sentences, similar to the standard Te-form (meaning \"\"and\"\"), but it is primarily used in writing or formal speech. It gives a more polished, literary feel compared to the standard Te-form.<br><br>Verbs: Use the Masu-stem (e.g., tabe instead of tabete).<br>Negatives: Use the Nai-stem + zuni (e.g., tabezuni instead of tabenaide).<br>I-Adjectives: Remove the te from kute (e.g., yasuku instead of yasukute).\"",
              "sentences": "私は学校に<b>勤め</b>、ユキはうちで働いている。<br>(Watashi wa gakkou ni tsutome, Yuki wa uchi de hataraite iru.) - I work at a school, and Yuki works at home.<br><br><b>食べずに</b>仕事に行きました。<br>(Tabezuni shigoto ni ikimashita.) - I went to work without eating.<br><br>勉強<b>せずに</b>テストを受けた。<br>(Benkyou sezuni tesuto o uketa.) - I took the test without studying.<br><br>材料を<b>混ぜ</b>、オーブンを１００度にセットし...<br>(Zairyou o maze, obun o hyakudo ni setto shi...) - Mix the ingredients, set the oven to 100 degrees, and..."
            },
            {
              "id": "mlbio2vfo",
              "point": "～てくる",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses a change that began in the past and has continued up to the present moment (\"\"have begun to X\"\"). It implies a process or emergence of a state. It is often used with verbs of change (like gaining weight, increasing, becoming).<br><br>Contrast: Te iku (will go on doing/will begin to) vs. Te kuru (have begun to/came to be).\"",
              "sentences": "日が短く<b>なってきた</b>ね。<br>(Hi ga mijikaku natte kita ne.) - The days have begun to get shorter, haven't they?<br><br>最近ちょっと<b>痩せてきた</b>。<br>(Saikin chotto yasete kita.) - I've begun to lose a little weight recently.<br><br>納豆が食べられるように<b>なってきた</b>。<br>(Nattou ga taberareru you ni natte kita.) - I have begun to be able to eat natto (over time)."
            },
            {
              "id": "pywwxt9wb",
              "point": "～しかない",
              "meaning": "\"Emphasizes that there is \"\"nothing but\"\" or \"\"only\"\" a small amount of something. It conveys a negative nuance of insufficiency (i.e., \"\"I only have 5 minutes\"\" implies 5 minutes is not enough).<br><br>Rule: Always followed by a negative verb.\"",
              "sentences": "昨日会社に二人<b>しかいなかった</b>。<br>(Kinou kaisha ni futari shika inakatta.) - There were only (nothing but) two people at the company yesterday.<br><br>会社まで五分<b>しかかからない</b>。<br>(Kaisha made gofun shika kakaranai.) - It takes only (nothing but) five minutes to get to work.<br><br>今日は納豆<b>しか食べなかった</b>。<br>(Kyou wa nattou shika tabenakatta.) - I didn't eat anything but natto today."
            },
            {
              "id": "qph65bijb",
              "point": "～ことにする",
              "meaning": "\"Expresses a firm decision or determination to do (or not do) something. When used in the continuous form koto ni shite iru, it means \"\"make it a rule to do X\"\" or \"\"habitually do X based on a firm decision.\"\"\"",
              "sentences": "それを言わない<b>ことにする</b>。<br>(Sore o iwanai koto ni suru.) - I am determined not to say that.<br><br>明日早く行く<b>ことにする</b>。<br>(Ashita hayaku iku koto ni suru.) - I am determined/have decided to go early tomorrow.<br><br>ジムの後プロテインを飲む<b>ことにしている</b>。<br>(Jimu no ato purotein o nomu koto ni shite iru.) - I make it a rule to drink protein after the gym."
            },
            {
              "id": "klm0cox9o",
              "point": "気がつく / 気をつける / 気に入る",
              "meaning": "Covers three common idioms using the word Ki (spirit/feeling):<br>気がつく (Ki ga tsuku): To notice or realize.<br>気をつける (Ki o tsukeru): To be careful of (more specific than just ki o tsukete).<br>気に入る (Ki ni iru): To be fond of / to like (used for specific items/experiences found agreeable, not general categories).",
              "sentences": "後ろにいたことに<b>気がつかなかった</b>。<br>(Ushiro ni ita koto ni ki ga tsukanakatta.) - I didn't notice that you were behind me.<br><br>レッスンスライドの間違いに<b>気がついた</b>。<br>(Ressun suraido no machigai ni ki ga tsuita.) - I noticed a mistake on the lesson slide.<br><br>車に<b>気をつけて</b>。<br>(Kuruma ni ki o tsukete.) - Be careful of cars.<br><br>最近クラシック音楽が<b>気に入っている</b>。<br>(Saikin kurashikku ongaku ga ki ni itte iru.) - Recently, I am fond of classical music."
            },
            {
              "id": "sj0bsclbj",
              "point": "～おかげで",
              "meaning": "\"This grammar point is used to express gratitude or attribute a positive result to a specific cause. It translates to \"\"Thanks to...\"\" or \"\"Because of...\"\". It is generally used for good outcomes.\"",
              "sentences": "たくさん練習した<b>おかげで</b>、発表は大成功しました。<br>(Thanks to practicing a lot, the presentation was a big success.)<br><br>好き嫌いがない<b>おかげで</b>、食べ物を無駄にしない。<br>(Thanks to not being picky, I don't waste food.)<br><br>今日は仕事が楽な/暇な*<b>おかげで</b>、早く帰れた。<br>(Thanks to work being light/easy today, I was able to go home early.)<br><br>家族の<b>おかげで</b>、大学に入れました。<br>(Thanks to my family, I was able to enter university.)"
            },
            {
              "id": "57wxdmezu",
              "point": "～ば～ほど",
              "meaning": "\"This pattern expresses a proportional relationship: \"\"The more [A], the more [B].\"\" It repeats the verb or adjective twice—first in the conditional 'ba' form, then in the dictionary form followed by 'hodo'.\"",
              "sentences": "年を取れ<b>ば</b>取る<b>ほど</b>、考え方が固くなる。<br>(The older you get, the more rigid your way of thinking becomes.)<br><br>運動すれ<b>ば</b>する<b>ほど</b>、体力がつく。<br>(The more you exercise, the more stamina you gain.)<br><br>そのアイドルが人気であれ<b>ば</b>人気である<b>ほど</b>、チケットが取れない。<br>(The more popular that idol is, the harder it is to get tickets.)<br><br>今が幸せであれ<b>ば</b>ある<b>ほど</b>、なくなるのが怖い。<br>(The happier I am now, the more I fear losing it.)"
            },
            {
              "id": "m1rlczp1j",
              "point": "まるで～のようだ",
              "meaning": "\"This structure creates a strong simile, meaning \"\"It is just like...\"\" or \"\"It is as if...\"\". まるで (Marude) emphasizes the resemblance. It can be used to modify nouns (～のような), verbs (～のように), or end a sentence (～のようだ).\"",
              "sentences": "このモンスターはとても可愛く、<b>まるで</b>犬<b>のようだ</b>。<br>(This monster is very cute, it's just like a dog.)<br><br>滝<b>のように</b>雨が降る。<br>(The rain falls like a waterfall.)<br><br>この家は<b>まるで</b>人が住んでいない<b>ようだ</b>。<br>(This house looks as if no one is living in it.)<br><br>悪魔<b>のような</b>笑い声。<br>(A laugh like a devil's.)"
            },
            {
              "id": "9w0u7ivjz",
              "point": "～ことになった",
              "meaning": "\"This implies a decision has been reached, often by an external force, a group, or simply how things turned out. It translates to \"\"It has been decided that...\"\" or \"\"It turned out that...\"\". The progressive form ～ことになっている is used for rules, customs, or scheduled routines.\"",
              "sentences": "今週末、バーベキューをする<b>ことになった</b>。<br>(It has been decided that we will have a BBQ this weekend.)<br><br>熱が下がったので、病院に行かない<b>ことになった</b>。<br>(Since my fever went down, it was decided I wouldn't go to the hospital.)<br><br>冷蔵庫が壊れたので、新しいのを買う<b>ことになりました</b>。<br>(The fridge broke, so it was decided that we would buy a new one.)<br><br>長野市のバスは、降りる時料金を払う<b>ことになっています</b>。<br>(It is the rule/system for buses in Nagano City that you pay the fare when you get off.)"
            }
          ]
